Hydraulic jumps are easily seen when turning on a faucet in the kitchen sink - when the water hits the flat surface of the
sink bottom, it creates an almost perfect circle of outward flow. This flow persists until a certain radius
at which point the water surface
"jumps" up to a greater height. This phenomenon has been well studied and is an incompressible flow analog of shock wave. In this
